File: Transport MEC Jacob Mamabolo will be acting in the position of Gauteng Health MEC for the next four weeks. JOHANNESBURG - Gauteng Health MEC Bandile Masuku will take a leave of absence for at least four weeks pending investigations in corruption allegations, according to the Gauteng Premier. READ: Dikos release statement denying tender corruption Premier David Makhura announced on Thursday that Masuku would be placed on leave until the investigation into a controversial deal between the province and amaBhaca King Madzikane II Thandisizwe Diko. Two tenders, amounting to a R125-million bill, were awarded to Royal Bhaca, a company owned by presidential spokesperson, Khusela Diko's husband. READ: Diko, Masuku to be subjected to Integrity Committee Makhura said he is disappointed that one of his top-performing MECs is being accused of corruption. Transport MEC Jacob Mamabolo will be acting in the position of Health MEC for the next four weeks.